Speaker 2: Yes, it sure is! I had to pull back out my winter coat. I thought we were done with this weather.

Speaker 1: Oh, you know how New England weather can be. One day it's spring, the next day winter is back with a vengeance. 

Speaker 2: That's so true. I wish it would make up its mind. Anyway, how's your garden coming along? 

Speaker 1: It's doing alright, had to cover the tomatoes last night to keep them from the frost. You know, it's a bit of a hustle, but it's worth it.

Speaker 2: I can imagine. I've always admired your dedication to your garden. It's not something I have the patience for.

Speaker 1: It does require a lot of patience, yes. And speaking of patience, I bet you need a lot of it in your studies too. What are you studying again?

Speaker 2: I'm studying psychology. It's fascinating, but you're right, it requires a lot of patience and reading.

Speaker 1: Well, it seems like our jobs, though different, have some similarities. It's all about problem solving and understanding at the end of the day.

Speaker 2: Yeah, you're right. It's nice to see how these skills can be applied to different areas. 

Speaker 1: Absolutely. So, what are your plans after graduation? Do you plan on practicing as a psychologist?

Speaker 2: I'm still considering my options. I might go into research or maybe clinical practice. It's a tough decision.

Speaker 1: It certainly is, but whatever you decide, I'm sure you'll excel. Just keep applying that problem-solving mindset.

Speaker 2: Thanks for the encouragement. I really appreciate it.

Speaker 1: You're welcome. Well, it's been nice chatting. I better go check on those tomatoes. Have a great day!

Speaker 2: You too! Good luck with your gardening.
